## Loose Emerald Cut Diamond Price by Color Grade

The emerald cut's long, open step facets show color more than any brilliant cut. Color matters more here than in a round or cushion.

| Color Grade | What You See | Recommended? |
|---|---|---|
| D–F | Truly colorless — the long table shows pure white in all lighting | Yes — ideal for emerald cut |
| G | Near-colorless — very slight warmth visible in certain lighting | Yes — excellent value |
| H | Slight warmth visible in the long table under daylight | Borderline — white gold setting only |
| I–J | Noticeable warmth in the step facets | No — avoid in emerald cut |
| K+ | Yellow tint clearly visible | No |

For white or platinum settings, D–G is the target. For yellow gold, you can push to G–H because the metal warmth neutralizes slight color in the stone. Never go below H for an emerald cut in any setting — the long table broadcasts color in a way that cushion and oval cuts do not.

For more detail on how color behaves in an emerald cut, see the full [emerald cut diamond](https://diamondcritics.com/emerald-cut-diamond/) guide.

---

## Loose Emerald Cut Diamond Price by Clarity Grade

VS1 is the floor. This is not a preference — it's a rule based on the emerald cut's architecture.

| Clarity | VS1 | VS2 | SI1 | SI2 |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Eye-clean in emerald cut? | Yes — always | Sometimes | Rarely | Never |
| Risk of visible inclusion? | Very low | Moderate | High | Certain |
| Recommended? | Yes | Sometimes (must check video) | No | No |

Brilliant cuts — round, oval, cushion — hide inclusions in their tiny facets. The emerald cut does the opposite. Its large parallel step facets act as magnifying windows. An SI1 that's eye-clean in a round brilliant will show clearly in an emerald cut.

VS2 is sometimes acceptable, but only with a detailed HD video review from the vendor. You must see the actual stone, not just the grade. VS1 is the safe choice. You buy it and you don't have to worry.

For the full clarity breakdown, the [emerald cut diamond clarity guide](https://diamondcritics.com/emerald-cut-diamond-clarity-guide/) goes deeper on this.

---

## The Lab Arbitrage Window

Between 2ct and 5ct, lab-grown emerald cut diamonds deliver value that simply doesn't exist in any other diamond shape or carat range.

The reason is the clarity tax. Natural emerald cuts require VS1+ clarity because their open facets expose every flaw. At 2ct, finding a clean natural stone takes you to $24,000+. At 3ct, you're at $63,000+. At 4ct, you're approaching $100,000.

Lab production removes the scarcity premium. D-FL and D-IF lab emerald cuts at 2ct cost under $5,000. At 3ct, under $11,000. At 4ct, you can find D-VVS1 for [$7,737](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — less than the natural 1ct D-VS1.

This is the Lab Arbitrage Window: the carat range where the natural scarcity premium is so steep that lab stones offer ten times the stone for a fraction of the price. No other shape has this gap as clearly as the emerald cut does.

The window works because:
1. Natural clarity is rare at 2ct+ emerald cuts
2. Lab production makes top clarity accessible at any carat
3. Emerald cut's step facets actually show the D-FL quality — unlike in a cushion or oval where you can't tell FL from VS1 in person

