## GIA vs IGI for Loose Emerald Cut Diamonds

Both certifications are valid for emerald cuts. The difference matters for how you use the report.

**GIA** — the industry gold standard. When you see a GIA certificate on a loose emerald cut, the grades are from the most conservative, most trusted lab in the world. GIA's natural stone grading has no equal. For natural emerald cuts at any price point, GIA certification is the standard you should target.

**IGI** — widely used for lab-grown stones. IGI's lab-grown grading is accepted across the industry. Almost all lab emerald cuts on the market carry IGI or GCAL certification. IGI grades are generally reliable for lab stones, though IGI is slightly more generous in color and clarity grades than GIA for the same stone.

**GCAL** — a strong third option for lab stones. GCAL's grading is conservative and its certificates include light performance data not found on GIA or IGI reports. The GCAL Ideal Cut grade for lab emerald cuts is worth looking for.

The practical rule: GIA for natural, IGI or GCAL for lab. Don't pay a premium for GIA-certified lab stones unless you specifically value the GIA name on the report.

For more on certification, the [emerald cut diamond](https://diamondcritics.com/emerald-cut-diamond/) guide covers the GIA no-cut-grade issue in detail.

---

## Loose Emerald Cut Diamond Ideal Proportions

This is the most important section for emerald cut buyers. Because GIA doesn't grade cut for emerald cuts, you evaluate proportions yourself from the certificate.

### Length-to-Width Ratio

The L/W ratio determines the shape's outline — how rectangular or how square it looks.

| L/W Ratio | Shape | Look |
|---|---|---|
| 1.20–1.29 | Nearly square | Chunky, compact |
| 1.30–1.39 | Slightly rectangular | Classic emerald look |
| 1.40–1.50 | Rectangular | The most popular range — elegant, finger-elongating |
| 1.51–1.60 | Long rectangle | Bold, statement |
| 1.60+ | Very elongated | Unusual — rarely seen |

Most buyers land in the 1.40–1.50 range. This is where the emerald cut looks most like itself — long, architectural, elegant. Below 1.30 starts to look like an Asscher cut. Above 1.55 starts to look too narrow on the hand.

The ideal L/W ratio for emerald cuts is a personal preference within 1.35–1.55. There is no wrong answer inside that range. Outside it, you start losing the character of the shape.

### Depth and Table Percentage

| Measurement | Ideal Range |
|---|---|
| Depth % | 60–67% |
| Table % | 57–67% |

Depth outside 60–67% means the stone either leaks light at the bottom (too shallow) or goes dark in the center (too deep). Table above 67% reduces the stone's apparent size from above. Both extremes hurt the visual performance you're paying for.

For a full proportion breakdown, see the [emerald cut diamond ideal proportions](https://diamondcritics.com/emerald-cut-diamond-ideal-proportions/) guide.

---

## Loose Emerald Cut Diamond Size Chart

Emerald cut dimensions by carat weight at the standard 1.40–1.50 L/W ratio:

| Carat | Approx. Length | Approx. Width | Face-Up Size |
|---|---|---|---|
| 0.50ct | 5.5mm | 3.8mm | Small — finger coverage is limited |
| 0.75ct | 6.2mm | 4.3mm | Modest — visible but compact |
| 1.00ct | 6.5mm | 4.5mm | Classic 1ct presence |
| 1.50ct | 7.5mm | 5.3mm | Noticeably larger — strong hand presence |
| 2.00ct | 8.5mm | 6.0mm | Statement size — the elongated silhouette shows clearly |
| 2.50ct | 9.0mm | 6.3mm | Bold — fills the finger elegantly |
| 3.00ct | 9.5mm | 6.7mm | Dramatic — unmistakably large |
| 4.00ct | 10.5mm | 7.5mm | Collector territory |
| 5.00ct | 11.5mm | 8.0mm | Extraordinary presence |

One thing unique to emerald cuts: the rectangular silhouette makes stones appear larger per carat than round brilliants. A 2ct emerald cut covers significantly more finger than a 2ct round. This makes size-per-dollar particularly favorable for the shape — especially combined with lab-grown pricing. For a detailed carat-by-size breakdown, see the [emerald cut diamond size chart](https://diamondcritics.com/emerald-cut-diamond-size-chart/).

